  "text": "## Audit Findings: Django Session Key Rotation Concurrency Safety\n\n### Key Rotation Entry Point\nThe `cycle_key()` method is implemented in `django/contrib/sessions/backends/base.py` at line 428 within the `SessionBase` class. This method is called during login to rotate session keys. It operates by: (1) saving the current session data, (2) calling `self.create()` to generate a new session key, (3) restoring the session data to the new key, and (4) deleting the old session key.\n\n### Session Key Generation and Creation\nThe session backend base class `SessionBase` in `django/contrib/sessions/backends/base.py` defines two critical methods:\n\n1. **`_get_new_session_key()` (line 194)**: Generates random 32-character session keys using `get_random_string()` and validates that the key doesn't already exist by calling `self.exists(session_key)`. This check provides basic pre-existence validation.\n\n2. **`create()` (line 463)**: Abstract base method that must be implemented by each backend. The docstring guarantees that it will \"Create a new session instance...with a unique key.\"\n\n### Database Backend Implementation\nThe database backend implementation is in `django/contrib/sessions/backends/db.py`, class `SessionStore`:\n\n**`create()` method (lines 68-79)**: Implements collision handling via a while-loop with retry logic:\n- Generates a new session key using `_get_new_session_key()`\n- Attempts to save it with `must_create=True` (forces INSERT via `force_insert=True`)\n- Catches `CreateError` exceptions and retries with a fresh key\n- The `save()` method (lines 114-137) raises `CreateError` when an `IntegrityError` is caught during database INSERT, signaling a primary key collision\n\nThis design explicitly handles key collisions by detecting them (IntegrityError on duplicate PRIMARY KEY) and retrying with a new key, ensuring no silent overwrites.\n\n### File and Cache Backend Implementations\nBoth alternative backends implement similar collision-safe patterns:\n\n**File Backend** (`django/contrib/sessions/backends/file.py`, lines 110-118): Uses OS-level file creation with the `O_EXCL` flag (line 137) to atomically detect collisions, catching `FileExistsError` and retrying.\n\n**Cache Backend** (`django/contrib/sessions/backends/cache.py`, lines 48-65): Uses cache `add()` operations (which fail on existing keys) with up to 10,000 retry attempts before raising a `RuntimeError`.\n\n### Concurrency Safety Assessment\n**Collision handling: YES - explicitly implemented across all backends.** None of the backends silently overwrite existing session keys. All use explicit collision detection mechanisms (database integrity constraints, file system atomicity, cache add operations) combined with retry loops to ensure uniqueness. The `cycle_key()` operation is therefore safe from concurrent key collision issues, as each new key is validated before returning from `create()`."
}

